<F P=101> Japan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Okinawa Reaction to Nuclear Accord Allegations </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Okinawa Reaction to Nuclear Accord Allegations </PHRASE></F></HT>
<H4>    Statement by Governor Ota </H4>

<F P=102> OW1205070394 Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO in Japanese 12 May 94 
Morning Edition p 1--FOR OFFICIAL USE ONLY </F>

<F P=103> OW1205070394 </F>
<F P=104>  Naha RYUKYU SHIMPO </F>
<F P=105>  Japanese </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Okinawa Governor Masahide Ota on reports that </F>
Japan and the United States signed a secret agreement on 
deployment of nuclear weapons in 1969] 
  [Text] Twenty-five years have passed since the Japan-U.S. 
joint communique was issued. Recently, however, it was reported 
that a bilateral secret accord exists. This report resulted in 
great shock and further anxieties among Okinawan residents, who 
eagerly hope for the removal of U.S. military bases. The 
Okinawa Prefectural Government considers this a serious matter. 
It will ask the central government to take steps acceptable to 
the Okinawan people to disclose the facts, and state its views 
on the three anti- nuclear principles. From the standpoint of 
protecting local residents' lives, livelihood, and properties, 
we will further seek a peaceful Okinawa with no "nuclear arms" 
and "military bases" by patiently appealing to both the Japanese 
and U.S. Governments to make efforts. 

</TEXT>

