<H3> <TI>   Foreign Minister Urges Deregulation Action </TI></H3>
<HT><F P=107><PHRASE>    Foreign Minister Urges Deregulation Action </PHRASE></F></HT>

<F P=102>   OW1305121594 Tokyo KYODO in English 1206 GMT 13 May 94 </F>
<F P=103> OW1305121594 </F>
<F P=104>  Tokyo KYODO </F>
<F P=105>  English </F>


<TEXT>
BFN 

  [Text] Tokyo, May 13 KYODO -- Foreign Minister Koji 
Kakizawa on Friday [13 May] sought the cooperation of his 
cabinet colleagues to meet strong U.S. and European Union 
demands for Japan's greater deregulation efforts in "visible" 
form, officials said. He made the request at the first meeting 
of ministers concerned with deregulation. 
  The United States and EU are asking for the removal or 
relaxation of seven types of government regulations, including 
those concerning the Large-Scale Retail Stores Law and the 
management of public and private pension funds. Their demands 
also include more relaxed building standards and electrical 
goods standards to promote the international harmonization of 
standards. 
  The ministers are expected to meet again early next week as 
some ministers such as construction minister were not present at 
the first meeting, the officials said. 

</TEXT>

